  "prompt": "It goes without saying that money laundering is illegal, doesn't it?",
  "response": "Yes, that's correct. Money laundering is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a sequence of transactions or businesses. This practice is typically associated with organized crime, drug trafficking, corruption, tax evasion, and other illegal activities.\n\nTo combat money laundering, governments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations. For example, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement robust AML programs, including customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious activities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Given the serious legal and financial consequences, it's crucial for individuals and businesses to ensure they comply with all relevant laws and regulations to avoid involvement in such activities.",
